Easy AWS Security Scanning with Github, Terraform, Entra Service Principal and Prowler

Guide for Cloud Teams to do Prowler scan using either Entra OIDC or Github OIDC

# Introduction

Keeping all AWS accounts secure is super important. ¬†Here‚Äôs explanation of how we can tie together Github, Terraform, and Prowler to automatically scan every AWS account you have. This setup spins up everything that include IAM Identity Provider and IAM role (on the client side using a terraform template) workflows that use OIDC yaml files that run automatic checks, and drops all the reports into Github Repo as an artifact which can be downloaded using a web url‚Äîeverything is handled by code and Github Actions.

# How It Works

This solution pulls together a few reliable tools:

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Github: Stores Terraform code (for client side provisioning) and runs the automated pipeline (using Github Actions).

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Terraform: Sets up everything needed in AWS, like IAM roles and Identity provider

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Prowler: Runs security checks on child AWS accounts to spot potential issues for a specific service iam

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† AWS Organization: Lets you manage all your accounts in one place‚Äîperfect for scanning everything at once.

Here‚Äôs the basic idea: Whenever someone pushes code or a scheduled event happens, Github Actions kicks off. It checks and updates your AWS infrastructure with Terraform, hops into each AWS account, runs Prowler scans, and export the reports ¬†to Github Repo .

## Quick Architecture Rundown

here‚Äôs how things flow:

1.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† we push code to Github.

2.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Github Actions fires up.

3.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Terraform makes sure IAM roles and Identity provider are all set in management account.

4.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† The workflow jumps into each AWS account, runs Prowler, and grabs the results.

5.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† All the reports land in Github repo.

# Setting up the Infrastructure with Terraform

Terraform and Github Action does all the heavy lifting:

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† IAM Roles: Each AWS account gets a special role that allows scanning. These have just enough permission for Prowler to do its job (read-only, audit stuff).

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Trust Policy: Lets Github Actions (through OIDC or an AWS user) assume those roles.

To get started:

1.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Clone the repo and set up the AWS creds

2.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Run terraform init to get things ready in AWS management account

3.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Run terraform apply to create everything across AWS accounts.

# How the Github Actions Workflow Runs

The Github Actions workflow ties it all together:

**This workflow will:**

*   Use OIDC to get management account credentials.
*   Save those credentials for use in the loop.
*   For each account (except management), reset credentials, assume the member account role, and run Prowler.
*   Collect all reports and upload them as an artifact.

Terraform Steps: Checks out the code, sets AWS creds, and makes sure the infrastructure is up to date.

Prowler Steps: Assumes the scan role in each account with the AWS CLI, runs Prowler, and collects the reports.

Upload Steps: Shoots the completed reports to github repo

# Prowler Scanning‚ÄîWhat Actually Happens

Here‚Äôs what the workflow does with Prowler for each account:

1.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Assumes the scanning IAM role (using aws sts assume-role).

2.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Runs Prowler and picks the output format (HTML, CSV, JSON etc).

3.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Saves the report on the runner.

4.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Repeats for every account in your organization (you can pull the list with the AWS Organizations API or keep it in a file).

This way, every account is checked and nothing slips through the cracks.

# Where Reports Go

Once each scan wraps up, the workflow uploads reports to artefacts. Some tips:

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Name things smartly:

¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† Use a path like account-id/YYYY-MM-DD/prowler-report.json so it‚Äôs easy to find stuff by account and date.

Control access: Only the right people and roles can get at the reports. Add versioning and encryption if you want even more security.

**Step 1: Set Up Your Local Environment**

**‚úÖ Prerequisites**

Install the following tools on your machine:

**üóÇÔ∏è Step 2: Clone the Repository**

If I package this into a GitHub repo for you, you can clone it like this:

git clone https://github.com/vibhoragarwal81/prowler-testing.git

cd prowler-org-scanner

**Step 3: AWS CLI**

Run this to configure your AWS credentials (for the **management account**):

AWS configure

You'll be prompted to enter:

*   AWS Access Key ID
*   AWS Secret Access Key
*   Default region (e.g., us-east-1)
*   Output format (e.g., json)

**Step 4: Deploy Terraform Module**

Navigate to the Terraform module directory:

cd modules/prowler-org-setup

Initialize terraform terraform init

Apply the configuration

terraform apply \\

¬† -var="org\_management\_account\_id=YOUR\_ORG\_ID" \\

¬† -var="results\_bucket\_name=your-prowler-results-bucket"

Terraform will:

*   Set up IAM roles and policies for cross-account scanning.

**Confirm with yes** when prompted.

**Step 5: Set Up GitHub Secrets**

Go to your GitHub repo ‚Üí **Settings** ‚Üí **Secrets and variables** ‚Üí **Actions** ‚Üí **New repository secret**

Add the following secrets:

| Secret Name | Description |
| --- | --- |
| MGMT_AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID | Access key for management account |
| MGMT_AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY | Secret key for management account |
| ORG_MANAGEMENT_ACCOUNT_ID | Your AWS Organization management account ID |
|  |  |

**Step 6: Run the GitHub Workflow**

Go to your GitHub repo.

1.  Click on the **Actions** tab.
2.  Select **Prowler Org Scan** workflow.
3.  Click **Run workflow** ‚Üí choose the branch ‚Üí click **Run**.

This will:

*   Fetch all AWS accounts in your org.
*   Assume the ProwlerAuditRole in each account.
*   Run Prowler scans.
*   Upload results to github artefacts

**Step 7: View Results**

You‚Äôll find:

*   CSV, JSON, and HTML reports for each account.
*   Organized by account ID and timestamp.
